<h3>Control Your Knowledge Panel</h3>
<p>A Google Knowledge Panel appears on the right side of search results for recognized entities. It displays your logo, description, social links, and key facts.</p>
<p>To earn and optimize your Knowledge Panel:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Claim your Google Business Profile.</strong> This is the fastest path to a Knowledge Panel for local businesses.</li>
<li><strong>Add Organization schema markup</strong> to your homepage. Include your name, logo, founding date, social profiles, and contact details. Use our <a href="/blog/schema-markup-seo-guide/">schema markup guide</a> for the exact implementation.</li>
<li><strong>Build a consistent entity across platforms.</strong> Your brand name, description, and key details must match exactly across your website, social media, Wikipedia (if applicable), and Wikidata.</li>
<li><strong>Verify your Knowledge Panel</strong> through Google's verification process once it appears.</li>
</ol>
<p>Your <a href="/blog/knowledge-panel-guide/">Knowledge Panel</a> is one of the most visible elements of your brand SERP. Treat it as a priority.</p>
<h3>Manage Third-Party Brand Mentions</h3>
<p>You cannot control everything on your brand SERP. Review sites, news outlets, and forums will rank for your brand name. But you can influence what those results say.</p>
<p>Respond to every Google review. Address negative reviews professionally and promptly. Update your profiles on review platforms with current information, logos, and descriptions.</p>
<p>Monitor brand mentions using Google Alerts, Mention, or SEO tools like Ahrefs. When a negative or inaccurate mention appears, address it directly. When a positive mention appears, amplify it through social sharing and internal linking.</p>
<p>For AI search specifically, monitor how platforms like ChatGPT and Google AI Overviews describe your brand. The information these systems use comes from your website, Wikipedia, and high-authority third-party sources. Keep all of those sources accurate and up to date.</p>
<h2>Entity SEO: Make Google Understand Your Brand</h2>
<p>Entity SEO is how you help Google recognize your brand as a distinct entity in its Knowledge Graph. This matters because Google does not just rank pages. It ranks the entities behind those pages.</p>
<p>A brand that Google recognizes as an entity gets preferential treatment: Knowledge Panels, rich results, and stronger associations between your brand and your target topics.</p>
<h3>Schema Markup for Brand Entities</h3>
<p><a href="/blog/structured-data-guide/">Structured data</a> tells Google exactly what your brand is. Add Organization schema to your homepage with these properties:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>name</code> (your exact brand name)</li>
<li><code>url</code> (your homepage)</li>
<li><code>logo</code> (your official logo URL)</li>
<li><code>sameAs</code> (links to all official social profiles)</li>
<li><code>foundingDate</code></li>
<li><code>contactPoint</code></li>
<li><code>description</code></li>
</ul>
<p>Also implement <a href="/blog/schema-markup-for-blog-posts/">schema markup</a> on your blog posts using Article schema with author information. This connects your content back to your brand entity.</p>
<h3>Build Your Knowledge Graph Presence</h3>
<p>Google's Knowledge Graph is a database of entities and their relationships. Your goal is to exist in that database with accurate information.</p>
<p>Steps to build your Knowledge Graph presence:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Create or edit your Wikidata entry.</strong> Wikidata is a structured data source that Google relies on heavily. Add your brand with accurate details.</li>
<li><strong>Build consistent references.</strong> Every directory, social profile, and third-party listing should use the exact same brand name, description, and details.</li>
<li><strong>Earn Wikipedia mentions.</strong> A dedicated Wikipedia article is the strongest signal, but even a mention in a related article helps. The exception: do not create a Wikipedia article yourself. It will get deleted. Earn it through notability.</li>
<li><strong>Publish on authoritative platforms.</strong> Medium, LinkedIn articles, and industry publications create additional entity signals.</li>
</ol>
<p>Your <a href="/blog/brand-entity-optimization-ai/">brand entity optimization</a> should extend to AI search platforms too. ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Google AI Overviews all pull entity information from the same structured sources.</p>
<h3>Connect Your Brand Across Platforms</h3>
<p>Entity SEO requires consistency. Google cross-references your brand information across dozens of sources. Any mismatch creates confusion.</p>
<p>Use this checklist to ensure brand consistency:</p>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Same brand name on all platforms (exact spelling and capitalization)</li>
<li>[ ] Same logo across website, social profiles, and directories</li>
<li>[ ] Matching business description everywhere</li>
<li>[ ] Linked social profiles (each profile links to your website and other profiles)</li>
<li>[ ] Consistent contact information on every listing</li>
</ul>
<p>The more connected and consistent your brand presence is, the stronger your <a href="/blog/entity-clustering-seo/">entity clustering</a> signal becomes. Google gains confidence that your brand is a real, established entity worth featuring in search results.</p>
